Given the set of rational function cards, complete the following steps in groups of 4:

Step 1 (12 min): Work as a group to sort the functions into three groups: those with a horizontal asymptote at the x-axis, those with a horizontal asymptote elsewhere, and those with no horizontal asymptote. Reminder from last week's discussion: A function with no horizontal asymptote will have an oblique asymptote. We do not need to worry about calculating those in this course. As you are deciding where each function goes, make sure each group member agrees. It is perfectly acceptable to pull out your notes from last class for this!

Step 2 (3 min): Choose two cards — one that has a horizontal asymptote, and one that does not. The instructor has created three groups on the whiteboard at the front of room for functions with no horizontal asymptote, a horizontal asymptote at the x-axis, and a horizontal asymptote elsewhere. Have two members of your group write your chosen functions in the correct groups at the front of the room. There is no need to write your name with these functions. We will then discuss as a class how your decisions were made.

Step 3 (28 min): Each group has a tabletop whiteboard and 4 different color markers. Each student has their own marker color and may not use any other marker colors. As a group, find all holes, vertical asymptotes, and x- and y-intercepts for one of your chosen functions. Your group's whiteboard is a collaborative workspace. However, the final whiteboard must be one cohesive presentation of your chosen function.

Each group member's marker color must be present on your whiteboard to show the individual contribution of each group member. For your first chosen function, Student A will write the work for the holes, Student B will write the work for vertical asymptotes, Student C will write the work for x-intercepts, and Student D will write the work for y-intercepts. If a key characteristic does not exist for your function, you may write "None" and give a brief explanation about how you know there are none.

If you finish quickly, begin may choose a second function to work with. For your second chosen function, Student A will write the work for the x-intercepts, Student B will write the work for the y-intercepts, Student C will write the work for the holes, and Student D will write the work for the vertical asymptotes. Meaningful discussion and deep understanding is more important than rushing to a second example.

Discuss with each other how you are able to determine each key characteristic without a graph. This should be a discussion, not individual work! It is important that it is not quiet as you are working. The person that is writing is not solely responsible for the work for that characteristic. They are simply the scribe for that piece. Each group member should be involved in the discussion.

Be sure to write these in their correct formats! Asymptotes should be written as lines, holes and intercepts should be written as ordered pairs.

Step 4 (2 min): Final Reflection (Provided written document for each group) - Were there any key characteristics that your functions did not have? What do you notice about the equation of that function that helps you recognize that that key characteristic does not exist for your particular function?

